MissionCommands.Message: Good morning {{profileName}}, and welcome to the Transposition & Docking lesson.
Today you will learn how to perform the Apollo Transposition, Docking and Extraction maneuver. Please read DOCKING & TRANSFER chapter in the Apollo Flight Manual for more details.
On Apollo lunar missions, the Transposition, Docking and Extraction (TD&E) maneuver is performed shortly after the trans-lunar injection burn.
The Docking system of the Command & Service Module (CSM) is a "probe and drogue" system. The system allows the Command & Service Module to dock with the Lunar Module.

The Apollo Docking system differences from the Gemini Docking Mechanism in that after docking and locking, the probe and cone mechanism can manually be removed to allow access between the two docked spacecraft.
Once both spacecraft are connected, astronauts can transfer from the Command & Service Module (CSM) to the Lunar Module (LM) and backwards.
This maneuver is performed in all lunar landing missions as it's used to take the Lunar Module to the Moon.
Let's get started! Keys are assumed the default configuration. Use the keys you have set in case of changes.
First, ensure that the A/C ROLL jets are powered. Set A1 to MNA.
Set C1 to MNB.
Set A2 to MNA.
Set C2 to MNB.
Next, let us set up the Digital Auto Pilot (DAP) parameters of the PGNCS. Key V48E V21E +11103E V22E +01111E. Press ROGER when done.
This will configure the autopilot to 0.5° deadband, 2.0°/sec max rate and B/D ROLL, 4 jets.

The craft can be commanded using either the backup Stabilization Control System (SCS) or by the Primary Guidance, Navigation, and Control system (PGNCS, pronounced pings). We will use the PGNCS today, but will set up the SCS as well.
Let us prepare the Stabilization and Control System (SCS).
On panel 1, set the MANUAL ATTITUDE ROLL switch to RATE CMD.
Then MANUAL ATTITUDE PITCH to RATE CMD.
And finally, set MANUAL ATTITUDE YAW to RATE CMD.
Verify that ATT DEADBAND is set to MIN.
The ATT DEADBAND defines the attitude hold precision. MIN will maintain the attitude within ±2 degrees, and MAX within ±5 degrees.
Next, verify RATE is set to LOW. This controls how fast the craft rotates.
FINALLY set TRANS CONTR to PWR.
On panel 1, set ROT CONTR PWR NORMAL 1 to AC/DC.
Then set ROT CONTR PWR NORMAL 2 to AC/DC.
The ROT CONTR PWR switches provides power to the rotational hand controller.
Now set BMAG MODE ROLL to ATT 1 RATE 2.
Next, set BMAG MODE PITCH to ATT 1 RATE 2.
Finally, set BMAG MODE YAW to ATT 1 RATE 2.
The Body Mounted Attitude Gyros (BMAG) is capable of detecting the spacecraft's rate. This information is used to update the known attitude, keeping track of the spacecraft’s orientation.
Ensure SC CONT is set to CMC.
Finally, set CMC MODE to HOLD.

Now, activate the COAS: Press "V" on your keyboard to bring on the [V]IEW SELECTOR panel, then hit [LH WINDOW] (hot key: [F9]). Next, press "C" on your keyboard to toggle the function bubbles, finally click on [TOGGLE COAS] on the right side of the window.

Next we will extend the Docking probe. Press "V" on your keyboard to bring on the [V]IEW SELECTOR panel, then hit [CTR SEAT]  (hot key: [F6]). On the top of panel, set DOCKING PROBE to EXTD/REL (up). The docking probe will spend 30 seconds extending, and its motion can be seen on the talkbacks above the switch. Barberpole means the probe is in motion.
Next, set EXTERIOR LIGHTS to RUN/EVA.
Now, set EXTERIOR LIGHTS to SPOT.
Next we will set the EMS to ΔV, this mode will let us measure changes to our velocity (delta-V, ΔV).
Set the EMS to NORMAL to begin detecting detla-V changes.
Ensure you have no angular rates, and that you are in the correct orientation. If the spacecraft is still changing attitude, wait until the maneuver is complete. Press IT'S STABLE to proceed.
Now you are ready to separate the CSM from the Launch Vehicle (SIVB). On panel 1, press the CSM/LV SEP push button.

Seperation! Ok, change view so you can see the EMS. Gently [TRANSLATE] in the forward direction [H] until the dV shows +/- 0.5 ft/s. Let it drift away from the SIVB for about 15 seconds. Press ROGER when done.

We will now do a full 180° pitch maneuver. You can look at your current attitude and add 180 degrees to it, or use the ORDEAL in ORB RATE. Then [PITCH UP] with a rate of about 2°/second until you align with the target and can see the Lunar Module from its top. Press ROGER when you see it.
Let us stop the relative motion between the CSM and SIVB. Gently [TRANSLATE] in the fwd direction [H] until the dV shows +/- 0.0 ft/s. Press ROGER when it is nulled.
Then [ROLL] 45 degrees to the LEFT and align the "T" shaped aim with the COAS. Press ROGER when you have the target of the COAS centered and aligned with the Lunar Module target.

Next [TRANSLATE FORWARD] gently while the "T" shaped aim is aligned with the COAS, and build a relative velocity of ~0.7 f/s. This will make you move towards the Docking Port of the Lunar Module with the Docking Probe of the CSM.
The T-shape has lights on it, and if the lights from the T shape and the backplate of the target is out of alignment, you need to maneuver. You will see this as you get closer and closer to it.
As you get closer and closer to the target, reduce the relative velocity towards ~0.1 ft/s, and carefully translate and use attitude control to align yourself with the target.
Use as much time as you need to get familiar with the relative motion, and when ready, complete the docking.
Docking is successful! Go to panel 2, and press the SIVB/LM SEP switch, and immediately [TRANSLATE] backwards gently.
Ok, the LM is free. Continue to [TRANSLATE] backwards gently to pull it out from the launch vehicle.
Congratulations, you just extracted the Lunar Module!
Today we used the CMC Attitude Hold mode to perform the turn-around maneuver, and visually decided if we had rotated 180 degrees. It is also possible to use auto manuever to do this.
This lesson teached you the basics of the TD&E maneuver. You can find the full procedures in the checklists. Great job, this completes the lesson.

Title: Lesson 10 - Transposition & Docking
Description: The Transposition & Docking maneuver involves separating the Apollo Command/Service Module (CSM) spacecraft from the SIVB launch vehicle, turning it around, and docking its nose to the Apollo Lunar Module (LM). The Lunar Module is then extracted from the adapter.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

In this lesson, you will learn how to separate the CSM from the Launch Vehicle (LV) SIVB, next you will use the CSM's translation thrusters for translating forward by moving gently the CSM away at a safe distance from the LM and the SIVB (no more than 100 feet), then you will turn around by pitching up the CSM at 180° until facing the Lunar Module (LM). after a little Roll to your left you will align the Lunar module Aim Crosshair with the Apollo CSM COAS, once it is aligned perfectly, you will translate forward until capturing the Lunar Module (LM). finally you will release the Lunar Module from the Launch Vehicle (LV) SIVB, then gently translate backward until separation is successful.
